title: 1989 Annual water management report 1990 Annual water management plan : Ruby Lake National Wildlife Refuge : Ruby Valley Nevada
name: 1989-annual-water-management-report-1990-annual-water-management-plan-ruby-lake-national-w
notes: Ruby Lake NWR 1989 Annual Water Management Report 1990 Annual Water Management Plan. Includes 1989 weather summary, water availability forecast, summary of 1989 water levels, effects of 1989 water levels on ecology of each management unit, and objectives. Precipitation the last five years (1985-1989) has been below the 12.85 inch 49-year average. During 1988 and 1989, only 9.26 and 9.36 inches of precipitation were received. With these low amounts in addition to poor surface and ground water storage from the previous below normal years, it is believed water shortages will continue to be extreme. Comparing this sequence of precipitation levels with amounts prior to 1961 when water shortages resulted in the South Sump decreasing in size to 20 acres, it appears to be similar, if not worse. During 1958 and 1959, only 7.70 and 9.76 inches of precipitation were received. Despite an above average precipitation year in 1960, the South Sump reached its lowest level during the summer of 1961. Precipitation received from November through February during the winters of 1956-57 to 1960-61 were below the 5.14 inch average. Snow pack on the mountains has been considered the most important moisture supplying spring flows. Precipitation during recent winters has not been low in consecutive years with 1985-86 and 1987-88 winters above and at the 48-year average. This may lessen the impact of the overall lack of moisture.
